  , issueTitle = "Promises/A+ for JS driver"
  , issuePullRequest = Nothing
  , issueUrl =
      "https://api.github.com/repos/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/issues/1395"
  , issueCreatedAt = 2013 (-08) (-30) 22 : 26 : 23 UTC
  , issueBody =
      Just
        "I would like to suggest that the JS driver use the [Promises/A+ spec](http://promises-aplus.github.io/promises-spec/). Callbacks are very important to support because they are the de-facto style, but that doesn't mean that promises should be unsupported. Modules *can* return a promise and still call a callback, allowing both to work. If you're on the fence with regards to promises, just consider that the following 2 examples do the same thing:\r\n\r\n```js\r\nr.connect({ host: 'localhost', port: 28015 }, function(err, conn) {\r\n  if(err) throw err;\r\n  r.db('test').tableCreate('tv_shows').run(conn, function(err, res) {\r\n    if(err) throw err;\r\n    console.log(res);\r\n    r.table('tv_shows').insert({ name: 'Star Trek TNG' }).run(conn, function(err, res)\r\n    {\r\n      if(err) throw err;\r\n      console.log(res);\r\n    });\r\n  });\r\n});\r\n```\r\n\r\nNB: the following uses [gen-run](https://github.com/creationix/gen-run) and JS ES6\r\n```js\r\nvar run = require('gen-run');\r\nrun(function* () {\r\n  var conn = yield r.connect({ host: 'localhost', port: 28015 });\r\n  console.log(yield r.db('test').tableCreate('tv_shows').run(conn));\r\n  console.log(yield r.table('tv_shows').insert({ name: 'Star Trek TNG' }).run(conn));\r\n});\r\n```\r\n"
